LED sticks for a 20x20 Kossel printer with linear rails.

Assembly

So here is the skinny, I got the idea from a picture I saw of a delta printer, either here or somewhere on the web, so I modeled up LED sticks to hold LED strip lighting powered off the Extruder 1 header on my Trigorilla board. The 20x20 mounts need to be printed in a set of 6 then mirrored in your slicer and printed again. This gives you a set for the right side of the extrusion, and the left side. Attach the sticks with m3 screws and m3 nuts, hand tighten so you can swivel the LED strips to your preference. Enjoy.

UPDATE - 27 Feb 2018
I have removed the motor mount from this collection because the design of the foam cowl it attaches too will not support the offset power and mass. Please see the "Power Set-up" section of the build page linked below for more information.

Build page:
http://www.itsqv.com/QVM/index.php?title=Strix_StratoSurfer

There are more parts available on my Stratosurfer parts catalog page found here:
http://www.itsqv.com/QVM/index.php?title=Parts_Catalog_-_Strix_Stratosurfer

I decided to try something different and having never gone down the Bixler style road (well except for a Penguin), the Strix StratoSurfer seemed like a good place to start. Also, after reading much about this plane, I decided to start with a larger motor/prop combo.

Here then is a collection of parts I did for the first build of this airframe.

General print notes:

  1. All parts were printed in PushPlastics ABS filament
  2. Motor mount and front & rear skids are printed at 80% infil, all others are 20-40%
  3. Print orientation is dependent on printer/slicer set-up, please rotate if necessary

title: Raspberry Pi 3 Case (With and Without Logo)

description.text:
Another Raspberry Pi case! I wasn't quite happy with any of the designs that I could find online, so I decided to model my own. This one is heavily based around Walter's sleeve case (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:604915) for the pi 2, and updates some of the clearances to allow the pi 3 to fit. I also chose to enclose the usb and ethernet ports completely, which increases the area in the interior to allow you to place a heatsink on your pi should you choose.

This case is designed to be pressure fit. The pi itself slides in easily, but the cap is pushed in firmly to hold everything in place. I used a vice to make sure that the cap was smoothly inserted parallel to the shell.

I have uploaded a Logo version with my name, as well as a blank version. Let me know what you think!

title: swap case for 65w macbook charger after wire replacement

description.text:
MacBook charger cables break very easily, and the price for a new charger is high. Although there are replacement wires that can be bought cheap and installed, the design of the original case makes it impossible to install the case back after opening, forcing us to use tape or glue which is not so strong and doesn't really look good.
so I made this case for my 65w charger of the late 2012 13.3 inch MacBook Pro A1425 to replace the old case.
it still keeps the ability to swap the power adaptor for different power sockets and the flaps click into place.
this might also fit other models' chargers but I can't be sure as I don't have the parts to test it with.
you will need 7 m3*25 bolts to install this case. and the case will end up a bit bigger than the original case as I have to leave space for the bolts.

This is an automatic fish feeder that is able to feed fish automatically. it uses a HiTEC HS-422 servo (or any servo with the dimentions of 1.6" X 1.4" X .8") that spins 180 degrees to deliver the fish food then 180 degrees back to refill.
the fish food for this feeder is the flake or small pellets. The food is kept in a hopper that can hold a significant amount of food.

Needed to complete:

  1. servo with a square.4" by.4" attachment (comes with HiTEC HS-422)
  2. arduino or some other type of controller to tell the servo when to move and feed the fish
  3. 3 mm bolts and nuts that hold the holding fins to the body of the fish feeder
  4. fish food (small pellets or flakes work best)
  5. fish to feed and a tank (mine is on a 10 gallon tank)

title: 125mm HEAT round
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
1:1 scale Russian 125mm HEAT round replica for size reference, display, cosplay, airsoft, etc.

It's a whopper... not for the faint of heart, it's a multi-day print designed for large printers (such as the CR-10).

The fins are designed with some clearance (about .3mm at 100% scale, which I've found works well in other projects), and should move after the print, though you may have to gently coerce them. I would have preferred to print them with the fins deployed, but that's too big even for a stock CR-10 (>300mm)

Please note, this is only an approximation. While I would love to have created one as realistically as possible (including threaded parts and accurate internal voids) as with some of my other models I had to compromise accuracy somewhat to make it more print friendly. Additionally there are several variants and therefore a variety of references, making an accurate portrayal challenging, but it was a fun exercise.

This is my only upload I have not yet test printed, as I will need to purchase additional filament first. If you decide to print one before I do and encounter some bugs let me know and I will see what I can do to fix it.

Update I created a 1/3rd scale version for those who don't want the full size one. It can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2758777

title: OctoPi with Camera Mount for Prusa i3 MK2S

description.text:
I really liked the round tower camera mount but I wanted to have a way to mount my Pi nearby as well partially because I think it looks nice that way and partially because I didn't feel like buying a longer cable for my camera, so I combined the tower with a Pi case to make it all one nice compact unit.

I had to block off the HDMI port to make it work, but if you are running Octoprint you aren't using the HDMI anyways. I provided a matching lid with the HDMI blocked and all ports but the camera port blocked and an otherwise solid top so you can add your own design if you want or do like me and slice it with a honeycomb infill and no top or bottom layers for a cool honeycomb mesh look. I used a bottom meant for a Raspberry Pi 3 but I think the only difference is the SD card access hole, and I'm pretty sure a Pi 2 can be used in the same base, but don't quote me on that. Any lids meant for the original case should work just fine only there will be a small slot for the top half of the HDMI port.

There is a 5mm hole in the base of the tower to add a support leg if you feel the need, I am using the anti vibration feet from the Prusa website, so I made a small ball with a peg to act as a stabilizing foot. It was designed to be easy to adapt to your needs if you have different feet on your printer, just make your own foot and put a 5mm peg on there to hold it in place. The whole thing is plenty strong so you could probably get away with no foot but I like the additional stability.

I provided a modified ball top that is solid if you want to put the camera straight on top of the tower, or a boom that allows you to bring the camera back closer since I had to move the whole thing out a bit to clear the Pi. If you are sure you will be fine with the camera on top of the tower I provided a file of the base with the ball permanently attached.

The whole thing can be mounted on either side but it was really designed to go on the right of the printer, if you mount it on the left the USB cables will kind of stick out.

I designed it with this camera case in mind: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2352964 but I'm sure you could use whatever you want as long as it clips on the ball.

UPDATE: I think the ball was transmitting too much vibration into my desk so I made an antivibration foot to match the ones I am using on the printer.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I didn't need supports on any components except for the little ball foot. Also this was all made with PLA because that's all I had, it should be fine as it doesn't get exposed to too much heat where it is.

UPDATE: The antivibe foot also needs supports.

I used leftover screws from the i3 kit to put the Pi case together, 2x M3x8 bolts with nylock nuts threaded all the way on upside down (so the flat part is against the bolt head) as spacers and screwed in diagonally to hold the Pi down and 2x M3x18 screws and 2x M3x20 screws to hold the lid down. In the original Pi case directions it calls for 4x M3x6 bolts to hold down the Pi and 4x M3x18 bolts to hold down the lid if you want to do it properly, I just used what I had available and made it work. If you do it like I did it I recommend screwing down the corner with the mini USB on the Pi, that's probably the place it will need it most. Also don't forget to zip tie the whole thing against the LCD as well, the friction fit is pretty good but you don't want it coming loose.

Reproduction through photogrammetry of a museum store model of an Egyptian sculpture. This is Taweret, a goddess with the head of a hippopotamus, limbs of a lion, and tail of a crocodile. The original sculpture dates to 664-610 BCE. It was found underwater in 2001 in Abukir Bay, and stands 96cm tall.

This capture was challenging due to the smooth, reflective surface of the model. I eventually resorted to dusting it with talc, but many defects remain. I've included the .obj and .mtl files if you would like to view the capture in color. You can clearly see the talc coating.

Hopefully you can still appreciate some of the beauty and power of the original.

Here is a model of fins that I designed for my surfboard.

Perfect for FCS model.

Once printed, apply a layer of fiberglass and fill the holes with resin (colored or not), as you wish ! ;)

You can get a good rendering with clear resin to obtain transparent fins.

This model was printed in ABS, if you want to get a smooth and shiny piece before applying fiberglass on it, you can smooth it with a piece of tissue soaked in acetone rather than spend hours sanding it.
The result is obvious.

Enjoy !

description.text:
These CR-10 feet are an homage to the famous Ennis Brown House, in Los Angeles' Griffth Park and designed by famed Architect, Frank Lloyd Wright. All CR-10 owners buy motor dampers, and that is really one of the best first steps toward silencing your CR-10. But if, as I do, you live in a multi-family structure, the noise to the neighbors may still be annoying. So I've put my CR-10 atop these bad boys, equipped with the speaker spikes and washer feet shown below. The spikes and washer feet were sufficient to silence the printer to my neighbors' satisfaction, but I didn't like the look. So this Thing is just to cover the mechanics of "hush!".

I'm using it with some speakers spikes (http://a.co/gJozeR4) inserted into the underside, and then sat upon some rubber washing machine anti-vibration/walking feet (http://a.co/8aQJDZf) which works really well. The washer file is just to help keep the speaker spikes' discs centered in the foot but it isn't necessary and may be something you'd want to replace depending on your choice of accessories.

The one you see pictured was a test-print with a low quality setting and high speeds, to prove the fitment. I'm going to re-print all four at high quality and lower speeds for better layer adhesion, and using a satin-silver filament. But this lets you see how it's assembled, and looks on the printer.

Happy Printing!

I used 100% because I was worried about the layers separating under pressure from all of the jerking and knocking the printer can do when it really gets going. But that is almost certainly a paranoid-noob move. Be sure your supports are at 1mm so that all of the narrow overhangs come out nice and square.

description.text: no support needed

Feedback from the adventurous folks that have attempted my GT2 belt upgrades for the Printrbot Simple shows that the belt ends are not the most friendly critters.  I too have struggled getting the belt to wedge in correctly at times, and don't care for cutting the belt every time I made an upgrade.  Therefore, I put together this little wedge that will lock the belt without the need to fold or cut.  Hopefully this will help make belt installs easier, and allow extra belt length to be kept for future upgrades.  
Simply interlace the belt teeth with the notches of the wedge, and insert into the V-slot of the belt tension blocks or belt ends.  
Enjoy.  
2014-03-25: Added the first revision of the part "GT2BeltWedgeNo1.stl" which is shown in the pictures. I felt this one was a little too flimsy, so I beefed it up to the "GT2BetlWedge.stl"

this measure works as follows. you place the hopper on the case. then you place the measuring cylinder into the housing. align the hole on to cylinder with hopper hole. then pour the powder into the hopper. then when cylinder is filled with powder turn the cylinder to dispense the pre-measured amount of powder.
the volume of powder is 1.7 cubic inches which is equal to about .12 cups. but it is easy to dispense more by simply turning the cylinder until the powder dont fill the cylinder . then you can just add powder and continue. so in about 10 activation's of the cylinder you will get about 1 cup. 5 activation's is about 1/2 cups.
activation means turning the cylinder to fill it, the turning the cylinder to empty it.
can be used for rice, flour, herbs, etc.

these stl files are in inches so you will probably need to convert to mm.

title: Mini 125mm HEAT
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is the 1:1 125mm HEAT round ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2758654 ) scaled down to 33%

For those not wanting to commit to the larger 1:1 scale 125mm HEAT round, I've created a simplified 1/3rd scale version that can be printed in a fraction of the time -- since simply scaling down the full sized version might cause issues with the tolerances.

In this case, I tripled the size of the gaps between parts that are supposed to move and fit together, so when scaled down it will still move. For simplicity I only included the major components (some of the internals that won't be seen are left out)

A test print of the fins at .1mm layer height was successful, though a few minutes of careful poking with an xacto knife was needed to get the parts moving,

title: Car Plastic Bag Trash Holder - For Sleeve Behind Passenger's Seat

description.text:
About

A while ago I looked for a plastic bag holder for trash and all I could find were things that clip onto the back of the passenger's headrest. I didn't like the way that looked nor works (if it was full wouldn't it be noisy when it moves? Also hard to reach), so I made this. It rests on top of the sleeve some cars have behind the passenger's seat so the driver can easily reach behind and put trash in it.

This was made as a personal project and is only being uploaded in case anyone else wants to use it. It isn't perfect, so I included the Fusion 360 project file so that you can modify it if you want to change anything.

Printing

Print settings do not really matter as long as it is printed with some infill as even when full it won't be handling a lot of weight. I recommend printing it in the provided orientation, and if your bed is big enough you can print the pieces side by side.

Joining the pieces

There isn't any print tolerance on the pieces that wedge together because I got lucky and was able to wiggle my parts together for a tight fit. I suggest just printing it and sanding it down a little if you have trouble getting it together.

title: Neje laser cover with fan
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a protective cover for the neje laser engraver dk-8-kz. It helps contain the laser light and even filters the fumes from the engraving process.

It uses a big 140mm externally powered fan with active charocal and HEPA filtering. The pieces hold to the original frame using strong neodym magnets on the existing screws and are easily removable. The front part holds a small 5x5cm window for laserproof glass. The back part has a slide door to allow bigger stuff being engraved.

Design Spark Mechanical file included to allow easy adaption to your needs.

IMPORTANT NOTE: I take no responsibility whatsoever regarding the safe use of your laser with this cover! Always protect your eyes with certified laser protection glasses. I would not trust my eyesight to the chinese glasses that come with the carver... And be aware that the cheap laser might be leaking more than the expected 405nm light (frequency doubling)!

1x active charocal filter mat 150x150mm
1x HEPA filter mat 150x150mm
4x M4x40 screw hex head
1x M4x10 screw
5x M4 nut
1x laserproof glass 50x50x5mm
1x dustproof mesh 100x120mm
12x Neodym magnets 8x3mm
4x Neodym magnets 8x2mm
8x Neodym magnets 5x1.5mm

General assembly

See the exploded complete .stl file to get an idea of which part goes where. Some parts need to be glued on. The magnets need some glue as well.

If you have any questions about the assembly, let me know. It seems that uploading pictures on thingyverse is a bit tricky. Half the time I can't see them... pity!

Kaboom! Exploded view. All cover parts are easily removable. Front part

The front part holds the small 5x5cm piece of laserproof glass and is fitted with a shutter for improved protection.

Add the glass into the fitting, then glue it on the cover.
Glue the hinge rectangle for the shutter on the fitting.
Fix the shutter to the hinge with some wire or a screw as axle.
Glue two magnets in the two holes on the top.

Back part

The back part has a sliding door to allow larger objects in.

Depending on your printers tolerance, you might need to sand down the door a bit.
Put a M4 nut in the door, put the door in the slides, then glue the stopper on the bottom (Don't forget that nut!).
You can then hold the door in the desired height by turning a small screw into the nut.

To make the NSA happy: Back door, wide open ;-) Top part

The top part serves as air intake and lets the air cool down the laser. The air is forced around a corner, so there is no direct line of sight into the machine. A dust grill prevents stuff from being sucked in.

Glue the plate with the cross-like structure on it to the other top-part (on the four structures that hold the bigger magnets.
Glue your dust-proof mesh on the frame AFTER glueing the four small magnets (5x1.5mm) into the frame.
Glue the four corresponding magnets into the top-part, be sure about the polarity!
Glue the four bigger magnets (8x2mm) that will hold the whole thing in place into the top part.

Removable dust-proof mesh with frame on the air intake. Be sure to get the polarity of the 8 magnets right! Fan & filter part

The fan sucks air and fumes out of the carver, then blows it through the charocal/HEPA filter. The 140mm fan might be a bit overkill. But due to its high flow there is no leakage of fumes even when the back door AND front part are open.

My 140mm fan needed an additional printed shroud, which you might not need depending on your fan. (In my case the gap between the fan and its case was too big, allowing the air to just return through this gap instead of being forced through the filter).

Just see the exploded .stl and photos to see what goes where.
Use the M4x40 screws to hold the fan in its case.
The filter and grid cover holds on its own. If not use longer screws.
Solder the switch between the fan and power-supply and put it into the small case on top.

Fan shroud (green) and M4 screw. Switch, the thicker cable goes to the 12V power supply.

description.text:
Gut's Dragonslayer from Berserk

----------------CHECK EDIT NOTES-------------

I never could find a full scale Dragonslayer so I decided to cut my own up.

No Handle file since it wouldn't be able to hold the blades weight. I recommend using PVC Pipe or Aluminum. No hole in the bottom of the hilt for this because people have different preference to how thick they want the handle.
I'm personally using a 1 inch PVC pipe, used Netfabb to make a hole about 8 inches into the bottom. (or you could just drill the hole) either way

Est - 300hrs to print all pieces with the longest single print about 25hrs

EDIT 1: - Parts weren't aligning properly with mirror so I adjusted the pieces, They should fit together better testing will happen.
EDIT 2: - First 3 parts were a little too tall for my printer (20cm height) So I re-cut them into four pieces to fit better. (side note - turn the pieces from corner to corner on the bed to fit)
EDIT 3: - Turns out the blade was a lot bigger than I thought, I didn't read the length right in the file. Original Blade Length was 80inches Much too large. I scaled the sizes down to 75% making total blade length 60 inches or 5ft Perfect.

title: Case for NodeMCU Motor Driver from doit.am

description.text:
This is a case for the DOIT.am brand motor driver shield for the NodeMCU dev board. I plan to use 3m double sisde tape to hold the board to the bottom. There is a single wall thickness on the terminal strip side which is meant to be cutout but should allow support for the long span. You may need to enable "detect thin walls" for it to print that part correctly.
I'm printing it now so I don't know how well the lid will fit. It may need to be scaled down to 99% if too tight. It should be printed upside down too in case it's the other way around when I upload it.

I added a button that goes through the hole. Depending on printer accuracy you may need to drill out the hole in the lid a bit. I printed with a 2mm brim and it came out fine. I used a small knife to clean the hole in the bottom and it kind of snapped on to the power button on the board. I was thinking if it is loose on the button, a small o-ring could help to keep it from riding up too high and off the button. I didn't want to design a stop in that might interfere with someone else's assembly.

Light Pipes seem hard to find so I may just make a hole for the power light too and leave it at that.

There is a skinny stake and a stake. The skinny took the walls down to 3mm. The thick is 5mm and takes an hour to print. I think I chose 5 percent infill.  I create two spike holes, but also used 1 spike. Make sure you put the spikes in first... I am not sure it is possible to pull the wood stake out afterwards. At the garden I think I heard one of the step areas bust, but the stake pushed in fine by hand the and fence looked pretty nice. The area is sandy, so I am not sure if the spikes are really long enough... I had a bunch of them though, so why not try. The reinforcement piece only fits the 5mm adapter. I just had a brainstorm of printing it the adapter in two pieces so the supports would be under the initial adapter. That is what they looked like from the store.

This is my take on a core xy conversion for the FT5. This is heavily inspired by the Hypercube Evo. Most of the parts needed for this will be found in the FT5 kit. Belts, pulleys, second linear rail(for x axis) 55&60mm screws, Titan Aero, pancake stepper(for extruder) and BLTouch will need to be purchased. As this is now you can only use a pancake stepper for the aero. I have included the step file for anyone who wants to help make other extruder mounts. This is setup for a second linear rail on the x axis but it will work with only one mounted towards the front. I realize this makes for a heavy gantry but with the provided firmware speeds of 80-120mm/s are reachable with minimal to no ghosting in the y axis of the print. This of course all depends on the model you are printing.

Also included is a copy of marlin 1.1.8 for this setup. YOU WILL NEED TO set your z offset, steps per mm and P.I.D. values for your printer as they will differ from mine. Build volume in firmware is set to 300x300x400mm but you can squeeze around another 40mm out of the z if you try ; )

[If you are using the stock board and drivers use this:
DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT { 80, 80, 400, 410 } (stock drivers with titan) CALIBRATE YOUR ESTEPS!!!]

I use lv8729 drivers on the stock board with 1/32 microstepping on x,y,z and 1/8 microstepping for my extruder. I feel like this gives me better performance when using linear advance with the titan extruder. So unless you have these drivers or the 8825 drivers you need to change your DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT to the above listed values.

E-Flite Timber Snow Skis

Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nn0KLkLK3VE

Summary

The E-Flite Timber is a fantastic little STOL plane that comes with big bush wheels and floats for flying off water. Many people use those floats for flying off snow as well, but I wanted skis. There are some options out there, but none of them meet all of these (in my opinion critical) criteria:

  • Easy to print without supports
  • Stock fit and finish (no modification to the plane)
  • Allow for limited travel of the skis to handle rougher terrain
  • Able to print all 3 skis at once (on an 8x8 print bed such as i3 style)
  • Does not negatively affect flying characteristics
  • Lightweight

These skis were made a little wider than many options, so that they could be shortened a bit and still have tons of surface area. They also fit on the stock axle with the stock landing strut with no modification, and have limited travel to navigate the terrain. They include a loop to hook a rubber band to, to keep the tips up while flying and landing.

I included the "test" files that we used when designing these. They are what we used to check fitment and travel of the ski. You can use them to test tolerances of your printer and determine whether or not you need to scale the model for it to fit well--without wasting plastic on the whole ski.

Printing

I printed these with .8mm nozzle at .2mm layer height, 20% infill, 2 shells top/bottom/sides. YMMV but this gave me a very strong part that was still plenty lightweight.

Preparation

Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T_lS3e4qoLI

I use warm (a bit cooler than boiling) water to soften the tip of the ski, and then use the front of a frying pan to shape the ski tip. Dip the ski into the water so that the tip is in the water basically up to the rubber band arch. Place the ski "right side up" inside the frying pan, and slide the tip into the edge of the pan to shape the front of the ski. Others have used heat guns and pringles cans with good effect, but I find the water to be more controlled as far as where the heat is going, and the frying pan gives a good shape.

You will also want to shape the front of the rear ski slightly so that it doesn't catch on the snow. Do not bend the rear ski up much, or it will strike the empennage. The two holes go in front, and the grooves go down.

Installation

The fronts should be relatively self explanatory. Remove the stock lock nut, slide the wheels off, put the wheels somewhere safe, slide the ski on, and then secure with the lock nut. Attach a rubber band to the arch on the ski, and then secure the other end to the landing struts where they meet the fuselage.

For the rear, remove the 3 screws holding the rear wheel on, remove the cover plate and wheel and place them in the same safe spot as the front wheels, and then use the stock screws to secure the rear ski where the cover plate used to be. the screws should be able to countersink down into the model.

description.text:
This is my take on an inexpensive Cartesian printer that should be relatively easy to build and easy to get good and consistent print quality. The Cartesian One is based on 2020 aluminium v-slot extrusion, some mini wheels and a lot of 3D printed parts. You should have access to a 3D printer when building this one!

Some parts can be easily changed due to the modular design. You can change the extrusion lengths to get a taller printer, different smooth rods etc.

Please note that some design changes have been made since the "old" photos were taken. I am no longer using a 2020 based bed design or the top corner plates. I have also changed the PSU mount so it no longer has an Integrated top corner plate.

On my build I have used 12mm smooth rods for the Y-axis, but parts for 8mm smooth rods are provided as well.

I decided to 3Dprint as many parts as possible including the 2020 corners https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2502931. I even printed the gantry plates and the spacers to keep cost and waiting time for shipments down. A few components are coming from the AM8 project and from some of the AM8 remixes. The x-carriage is a new version of my thing: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2469435 using wheels instead of bearings.

2020 v-slot extrusions for my build with a 220 x 220 build plate: (will obviously depend on your own build plate and the build height you would like)
2 pcs. 300 mm (X)
1 pc. 260 mm (top crossbar)
2 pcs. 390 mm (Z)
2 pcs. 380 mm (Y)
1 pc. approx 370 mm for the x-carriage (Probably best to cut that one to exact length when you have the other components printed and mounted)
Tap both ends of the y-extrusions, bottom end of the z extrusions and the top x-crossbar extrusion for M5 bolts.

I have changed the base plate for this printer from 2020 based to 3D printed, and are now using my thing https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2805351

  • You will need 20 teeth pulley and idler for X to clear the wheels on the x-carriage. You may use 16 or 20 teeth for Y belt. (16 teeth recommended).
  • 300mm T8 lead screws with nuts (depending on build height)
  • A lot of M5 bolts and t-nuts...

Wheels used in my build: https://www.banggood.com/3D-Printer-FlatV-Type-Plastic-Pulley-Concave-Idler-Gear-p-1038551.html type 2. Or spend a little more and get wheels from the OpenBuilds part store.

Casing for the fan mounted on my cheap/crappy PSU (taken from the Anet A8 kit) https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2012944
Normally I stick to ATX PSUs on my 3D printers, but when I don't I still want a fan to keep things cool.

The test prints are printed at 0,2 layer height and at 60mm/s

Use a flat and stable surface for your printer!

Update 18.Jan.2018
Published a new x endstop to avoid potential interference with a gantry bolt.

Update 28.Jan.2018
Uploaded a simple drill template. Align it with the edge of the extrusion, secure with a M5 bolt and a t-nut and then drill 3mm pilot hole. The template is intended for 2020 and 2040 but only the pilot hole closest to the edge is relevant on this printer.

Update 4.Feb.2018
Uploaded a jig/tool to do precision cuts on 2020 extrusion with a hacksaw. Print with supports, 70% infill and use a strong filament. When using this, be careful not to cut past the extrusion and destroy the jig :-)

Update 11.Feb.2018
Uploaded new y-motormounts. The only difference is that the screw holes are recessed by 3mm to avoid having to source a longer M5 bolt for just these mounts. Use M5 bolts with head diameter < 9,5mm (like the low profile screws from the OpenBuilds part store, RatRig and others)

Update 20.Feb.2018
Uploaded bearing bushings/holders and rod holder for LM8UU y-smooth rods. This is an option to the LM12UU used in the original design.

Update 24.Feb.2018
Created a new "universal" base plate and improved the bearing blocks. I have done that to reduce mass from the previous 2020 based bed design. (and reduced the need for parts and fasteners). Files have been uploaded/replaced here. See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2805351 for more details about the base plate.

Update 06.March 2018
Uploaded a new PSU cover as the previous version could interfere with long heat bed screws when using the new base plate.

This a simple sleek shell to create a raspberry pi based portable game station.

I've added two versions of the shell:

2nd: Front and back cover are split into 3 parts each (for smaller printers)

description.text:
Yet another frame for an Inductrix FPV / TinyWhoop with separate VTX and Camera. I positioned the camera below the frame to keep the size small and durability up, but mostly because I think it looks cool. Due to the construction of the frame, it's also possible to use multiple colors of plastic for a unique look.

I decided to make the frame print in two separate pieces, which are glued back to back. This allows everything to print flat on the bed without supports for best print quality and strength. All together, with canopy, the frame weighs about 4g. My weight without battery is 20g.

I have included two versions. One uses MCPX batteries at 300mah capacity, and another should fit standard batteries.

print_settings.Printer:: R1 ABS + PLA Model

description.text:
Top mount spool holder for Robo 3D R1 and R1+

Ground up redesign inspired by https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1773428 and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:158289. Wanted something that would hold the wheels a little more ridged and fit the shape of the R1 a little closer.

2018-01-25 Update
It turns out the half filament guide on each side of the support really only works when they are flush, but if even a little apart the filament can get snagged. So I cut out the space needed for the stock filament guide so that can always be used. Doesn't affect stability since the entire support is 30 cm wide (dictated bu the inline skate shaft). Haven't printed the new one yet but will upload pictures as soon as I do.

2018-01-21 Update
Needed to print using a very small spool and the old version wouldn't support it. The new version insets the screw heads on one side so the supports can be pressed flush against each other. A filament guide hole was also added to the middle.

Notes:

I printed the wheels without supports and they looked ok, but with supports (which popped out easy) I saw less variation in the edge when I spun the wheel.

I use Cura for slicing and when putting the spacer onto the bed it shows up 10x larger for some reason. Clicking scale and moving the decimal point for one of the axises (with proportion constraint) shrinks it back to it's designed size and it prints fine. Not sure if this would happen in other programs. Should have an OD of 8.04

Assembly
  • push the spacers into the bearings
    • they will be tight, just cram them in there
  • push the bearings into the wheels
    • these should also be tight
  • assembly with the washers on each side of the wheel
Hardware
  • 4 skate bearings 8mm, ID 22mm OD. I used these
  • 4 Inline Skate Wheel 15/64" Shafts. I used these
  • 8 washers that fit the skate shafts but less then 16mm OD (so doesn't interfere with rotating part of bearing)

author: Elzariant

description.text:
A water cooled heatsink for E3D hotend.

After reading a lot of informations there:

https://well-engineered.net/index.php/en/86-community-water-cooling
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:247599
http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?336,765316
http://www.instructables.com/id/Water-Cool-Your-3D-Printer-Nozzle-the-Cheap-and-Ea/
https://forum.e3d-online.com/threads/e3d-water-cooled-mod.53/

I remixed all these good ideas to create my own watercooling block.

The prototype was made without a lathe.

What you need:

  • A E3DV6 heatsink (or a clone…).
  • Some cold solder joint.
  • A B20 jacket ( 5 euros on Ebay…).
  • A M7 bolt (kinda hard to find… In france, you’ll find some in old hinges.

  • A 2,5 drill bit and a M3 taper.

  • A lathe (or a cheap drill that you can destroy)
  • A file
  • Some sand paper
  • A saw
  • Some knowledge about lathing.

The operations are easy:

  • Cut the head of the bolt
  • Cut the groovemount (if you want to use my kind of mount) PHASE1
  • Screw the bolt in the heatsink
  • Attach the bolt in the drill chuck
  • Attach the drill to your work bench
  • Turn the part like in a lathe (This is the hardest part. Be careful !) PHASE 2
  • Check the external diameter of the part (It should have a 20 mm diameter)
  • When the part is done, fill the 20mm fins with some cold solder joint (I mean really fill it!, you should have too much material but it’s nice
  • Put the part back in the drill and turn it back to 20 mm PHASE 3
  • Drill the heatsink with the drill jig PHASE 4
  • Wash the part with demineralized water
  • Put on the B20 jacket , fill it with with water and let it sit one night (to check the sealing)

description.text:
After lots of flying and changing this is my favorite mod for the UMXs in winter! they also work great on bigger planes like the Timber for a tail ski. Rig a small and light bungee or rubber band to the ski tips to hold them up and and light weight fishing line or floss to the rear to keep them from flipping all the way up, you just need the tips up when in a flat flying attitude. Best to buy a replacement set of main gear for your UMX and mod them so you can swap back and forth. The stock tail wheel works fine in even light snow and can be used as a break by pulling back hard on the elevator.

On a winter flying side note, keep the batteries in your pocket so they stay warm and add a thin section of closed cell foam or thick tape to cover the battery. After 5/10 flights the main board inside will have had enough of the cold and will act funny. Oh and make sure you skid/drift around some ice Alaskan style!

It's finally here!
See instructions for details. Many parts are optional.
Early test flight: http://youtu.be/IVNpG9oJvUg
I modified Thingiverse user ennui2342's tricopter body, based off of David Windestal RCExplorer tricopter, to support the stronger, more common (in the US) 1/2inch wood dowels. Other modifications were made as well. I also loosely based my landing gear/motor mounts off of jphillips' designs. The vibration dampening bottom plates among other features are unique to this tricopter. Update: I added "optional-plate_larger_motor_mounts_kit.stl" which supports larger (unnecessary) motors that use an 18.9/25mm through 25/25mm mounting hole spacing. Update 2: I don't know if there is a demand for them, but I designed extra-long versions of the landing gear/motor-mounts (22mm taller). They are published as "optional-plate_larger-longer_motor_mounts_kit.stl" and "optional-plate_standard-longer_motor_mounts_kit.stl" Update 3: I added a bonus IMU shield for exposed IMUs and flight control PCBs (imu-shield.stl). View later picture to see how it is mounted. You will need some VHB tape and soft foam as well. This not only protects the IMU, but also mitigates undesired noise from exposed digital barometers. (not included in the "full plate") Update 4: Fixed and reuploaded "optional-plate_3_esc_clips.stl". Original file was malformed and causing errors in some slicers. Update 5: Added "upgraded-optional-gopro_fpv_plate.stl" as an upgrade to the old multipurpose FPV plate + GoPro shoe. This package is now more rigid and strictly designed to be pared with the (unchanged) GoPro shoe. It should mitigate any resonant vibration issues caused by flexing of the plastic. Simply mate the top of this plate with the top of the battery plate using glue or tape and re-thread your zip-ties. The slanted face should be face down. (not included in the "full plate") Update 6: Added an larger optional countersink plate. Perfect for larger flight controllers, GPS units, and other bits of extra hardware. Tip: use wide strips of Velcro under this plate for easy access to the screws underneath. Quick specs:
Here is what I currently fly with this frame. MANY other hardware choices will also work just as well or perhaps a bit better.
-Turnigy 5000mAh 3S 40C LiPo
-Multistar 3525-850Kv Outrunner
-Turnigy Plush 25A ESC
-APC 13x5.5MR(P) props
-BMS-385DMAX Digtal Servo For a full, more detailed write-up, visit: http://goo.gl/K1WBVQ

*See notes.

Notes: Infill for the motor mounts should be between 60% to 100%. and should be printed with a high temperature tolerant plastic, such as ABS. (PLA will work, but will also fail spectacularly if your motors get too warm.) The infill for the main frame pieces can usually be anything greater than 25-35%.

For more details and pictures, visit the link at the bottom of this section.
Print quantities are stated in file names (likely just one of each) and optional extras. The optional cable and ESC clips are highly encouraged.
Some things you will most certainly need for the frame:
  • 3M VHB tape
  • 5mm wide zip-ties
  • 13x 25mm M3 socket cap screws
  • 13x M3 Nylock nuts
  • 1x 35mm M4 socket cap screw
  • 1x M4 Nylock nut
  • 3x Large soft rubber bumpons or misc. rubber (at least 7mm tall). Ear plugs, rubber tubing, Sugru blocks, or even traditional rubber ball dampeners are some other fair alternatives. (you will also need glue if applicable)
  • 1/2 inch (12.7mm) square wooden dowel (2x 350mm + 1x 320mm)
    • Aforementioned ESC clips will support up to about 25mm wide ESCs. These include Turnigy Plush 18A, 25A, and possibly 30A ESCs among many others.
    The motor mounts will support most standard outrunner mounting patterns from 16m-25mm diagonals . You will need to use 8mm or 10mm M3 socket cap screws to mount your motors, the screws that came with your motors might not suffice.
    Use 25mm M3 socket cap screws with M3 Nylock nuts to build the frame and secure the motor mounts.
    For the arms, cut two 350mm lengths of 1/2inch (12.7mm) square wooden dowel and one 320mm length of the same dowel. Drill M3 holes 15mm from each end. This will give you a frame which will measure roughly 660mm between each motor shaft.
    For the yaw hinge, use one 35mm M4 socket cap screw with M4 Nylock nut. Insert the screw from the inside out; the nut should be on the motor mount end. Tighten this firmly then back off slightly, you may need to sand/file the butting edges for smooth operation. a 16.5g servo should be able to move this with little effort and little play. White lithium grease may help. You may need to bore out these holes or apply tape to the screw depending on your printer.
    Affix the vibration damped battery plate and any optional extra plate (FPV or blank/AUX) as per the pictures in the write-up below. You will need medium-sized zip-ties (5mm width). Use any soft material that is at least 7mm tall to absorb vibrations; I used small blocks of latex foam wrapped in tape.
    For a full, more detailed write-up, visit: http://goo.gl/K1WBVQ

comments.text: I'm currently using a hybrid design.. many of your parts (the handy electronics boards, legs and yaw) with my own body frame; similar to yours (I also went by David W's frame :) .. mine doesn't seem very aerdodynamic so maybe I've got too much material (its much squarer), and one notable difference is .. I've been trying different approaches to locking in the arms.
comments.author: skeezix

comments.text:
That's good to hear! Nice work. I think the folding arms help considerably during crashes, even in tail-in/backwards crashes. A screw/pin wouldn't really allow this. Needless to say, there are still a lot of nice multicopter frames out there that don't have the ability to fold up. Everybody has a preference. The hobby is becoming extremely affordable now too, so a totaled frame will only put you back a couple of bucks.
Also, if you are finding your arms to be too loose on my version, try tightening the main frame bolts and/or file down the tops of the side-arm end stops (so the center plates fit closer together).
Also also, every gram counts on these things. Ideally you'll want to aim for a setup that has at least a 2-to-1 lift to weight ratio. eCalc is great for this.
comments.author: skeezix

comments.text: ecalc is amazing :) I'm using over-large batteries I think (4000mAh and 6000mAh) .. they're big heavy beasties, easily the heaviest thing on there. Surprisingly, my wiring is pretty heavy as well.. perhaps used too thick stuff (with silicon high temp sheath too.) I'm not sure how much a gram here or there matters, when throwing these nasty batteries on there :) .. I wonder, if just halving the battery size would improve flight characteristics?
comments.author: Physics_Dude

comments.text:
eCals is great indeed. If you don't have one, you definitely need to get a small kitchen scale and find your all-up-weight. This number, along with local temp/pressure/elevation, are quite critical in eCalc's calculations. If you need something to reference, my whole tricopter, similar to whats seen above, without a camera or battery weighs exactly 910g at this moment (includes forward and rear-facing night flying LEDs, hint hint). My bare 660mm frame without electronics weighs 205g.
My thrust to weight ratio is currently 2.5-to-1, but I aim to upgrade to a 4S power system in the future which requires new motors, props, and ESCs. By then I should have something that really cooks.
comments.author: skeezix

comments.text: Also ..
comments.author: skeezix

comments.text: Yes, I had this copter fall about 80ft onto concrete due to loose motor bolts once. I learned from this though, USE THREAD LOCKER!. Also, make sure you are not over-taxing your motors. If they get too hot (~60C+ for plastic mounts), they will soften the plastic and pull the screw heads straight through the mounts. I know this from experience. It also wouldn't hurt to tighten them while everything is warm. If you are in a pinch, a DIY wooden insulator for both sides of each mount might be your best bet.

comments.text: Trying to learn: What made you select the 12" props anyway? (to me, the combination of prop size and pitch, kv versus lift, is pretty black magic; most people tend to use what their contacts use, or what they find as a working thing in a forum, etc.)  You've got pretty large boom length and large props, which should promote stability (great for a learning copter :) .. I imagine reducing the prop size from 12" down to 10" or 9" should be okay, and maybe reduce the boom size onch inch on each (though the weight for wood shoudl be negligible difference there).  mini-copters move fast but are hard to learn and keep stable (especially with wind etc), so I've been aiming pretty big .. but keeping size down a little may be nice.

If your front arms are folding in flight, you need to either tighten the four 25mm bolts nearest to the arms more, or file down the tops of the two circular-ish spacers that the arms rest on in the open position (they are on the outermost sides of the center frame pieces and sometimes our printers put a bit too much ooze on the tops of them, causing the spacers to effectively become too tall).

description.text:
This is a forward swept wing which you can use with the fuselage of the “Speedy Red Midi Wing” https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2386440
The carbon rods pass all the way through, providing extraordinary
stability. You need one 8 mm tube and one 5mm tube, each 1000mm long.
These rods are so stiff and fit in so tightly, you don’t need to glue anything.
This makes changing a part very easy, in case it is broken or you want it in another color.
I havn’t had a chance myself to maiden it yet.

Recommended Print Settings
Attention
The wings are designed to print using 0.5 mm width, 0.3 mm height, 3 bottom and 3 top
layers, but one perimeter only.
Should you print thinner walls, the perimeter of the upper side will not stick well enough
to the perimeter of the inner stiffening construction.
If you apply thicker walls, the perimeters will not come out continuously in one
uninterrupted turn.
The layers must build up as if you were printing in spiral vase mode. Only then you get a
smooth surface on the upper side.
If unsatisfied with the results, try out 0.49 or 0.48 width in your slices settings. It
depends whether you use Cura, Slic3r, S3D or what yo have. I suggest you experiment with
some tests before printing the whole thing.

The second point is: Should you print lesser layer heights, the inner stiffening
construction will not connect well to the top and bottom layers. You will suffer a gap in
between.

All wing parts: layer height =0,3mm, width =0.5 mm

wing: 1 perimeter, 3 bottom layers, 3 top layers, hollow
wing servo: 3 bottom layers, 3 top layers, hollow
elevon inner: 7 (!) bottom layers, spiral vase mode
elevon outer: 3 bottom layers, spiral vase mode
elevon joint: no bottom layer, spiral vase mode

Specifications
airfoil: AR2610-S80 modified
wing span: 1000 mm
wing chord: 200/128 mm
aerodynamic center: 30 mm (12%)
overall weight: 730 g
wing weight 343 g (without components)
wing weight complete: 374
fuselage weight complet 356 g
fin weight 12 g
wing area: 16,6 dm²
wing loading: 44 g/dm²
longitudinal stability (Thies) STFs:
motor: Propdrive 28-36 1000KV
static thrust: 950 g (3S Lipo)
battery: Turnigy 1200 mAh 3S 40~50C Lipo
motor camber: tilted -4 degrees
side pull: none
propeller: Aeronaut CAM Aeronaut Carbon Classic 10 x 6"

author: Gophy

description.text:
A tripod mount for fixing an iPad to a quick release tripod... much stronger than using the camera mounting screw Note this design fits a (oldish) Miranda Titan TP20 tripod .. the rectangular hole in the pan/tilt head is approx 40x43x9.5mm more details on my blog rapman-education.posterous.com/ipad-tripod-revisited Note. files created in Creo2 (Academic edition) so I have also included Neutral (.neu) files that can be imported into many other 3D CAD programs for editing if required. These files have been printed sucessfully on a 3DS/Bits from Bytes 3D Touch printer... but should work on other machines. UPDATE....
i have always been a little bit concerned when using the tripod mount with my iPad, there was always the danger of the iPad slipping sideways and falling off.
No worries now! I've added some side clips and a middle slider. Add the middle slider to the metal upright then just thread some 20mm wide elastic (I got mine from an old pair of safety goggles) through the middle slider and then twice through each of the slide clips (like a buckle).

3D print the parts
Slide top plate over bottom clamp (glue if necessary)
Slot in a steel strip (12.75 x 1.6 x 210mm)
Heat the head of a 5mm x 18mm allen screw (bolt) and push into the plastic bolt head
Screw the bolt into the top clamp (the hole should be the correct size for the bolt to self tap into the plastic)
Slide the top clamp onto the steel strip (ensuring correct orientation) Slide iPad between clamps and tighten
Slot the bottom clamp into tripod QR mount
Take pictures and/or video

description.text:
This is a 3D printed and motorized Pinewood Derby car for our "Anything Goes" race. This race is meant to give the parents a car to build as opposed to building the scout's car for the child. The Thumb Slicer 2 (TS2) uses a 9V battery for power, an upcycled tray motor from an optical drive, an old hobby RC prop, 2 micro switches to start/stop the motor, and a main power switch. The wheels and axles come from the original Pinewood Derby car kit. There is a mess of wires wrangled through the body, and I used some sticky tack to hid the mess in the open square below the car.

Why the name, "Thumb Slicer 2"? The first version was made from a block of wood, hot glue, and some electronics. Upon showing it to my wife, it fell out of my hands and headed for the upholstered furniture... My wife reached to grab it, and the prop sliced her thumb!

Check out a brief overview of the car here: https://youtu.be/K2LVWnXM9-E

The Cub Scout Pinewood Derby can be a lot of fun and quality time spent with your child. Be sure to teach them as opposed to making the car for them!

title: Prusa i3 MK2S Filament Bearing Adapters

description.text:
I didn't like how the filament rides on the spool holder on my i3 so I decided to do something about it. We have this machine at work that devours a certain component but always leaves the ball bearings intact, and new parts come with bearings so I have a pile of like new 6005 ball bearings laying around. These are adapters to mount the filament spool on said bearings. The original parts are for 1kg Prusa PLA which has a 50.35mm internal diameter on the spool, I'll add to this post as I buy more filament with different spool sizes. This of course requires you to provide your own ball bearing, any size 6005 should work.

UPDATE 1/29/18: Added an outer shell for Hatchbox 1kg spools.

comments.text: I have successfully made a working key, there is a lot of chatter in the cuts the tolerances are not as perfect as a design using liner bearings and a shaft would be. Using a new blade helps, keeping the guide steady against the key and working slow and spraying it with water keeps from melting the holder. Using ABS instead of PLA would probably be a better idea. I am thinking of working on a better key clamping system, the screws can be stripped too easily.

This fan duct is inspired by the ones i found in this community but it's entirely made by myself. I wanted to get a different design, compared to the ones i found for this extruder, to improve the air flow efficiency. A great help comes from the MK8 Extruder mesh model (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1162319) made by @nikolastsr, that i used to design the object. Thank you.
The print is in two parts that need to be glued or fused together with a pencil torch or by friction welding (be careful). Feel free to not use supports, i used them but i think they can be avoided if the printer is good enough with overangles.
My printer is a Geeetech Prusa i3 Pro and the clearance between the bottom of the extruder and the nozzle is 42mm therefore i kept the duct bottom a little bit higher.

title: Lego_Trains_US_Style_Diesel_Plow
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is my own design of a U.S. railroad style, diesel plow seen on nearly every locomotive in the U.S. today. I just don't like Lego's plow that is standard with their locomotive sets because it is European-styled. Since my freight cars all use manually built trucks which don't have the European designed couplers with bumpers, I decided it was time to do the same thing for locomotives. I searched for some time without luck, trying to find a design that was already available which is why I designed my own. I used a combination of SketchUp and TinkerCad to do the design.

This model has an additional feature of the brake line/hose connector also included. You can see that in the photos. To complete the brake line and hose, I designed a brake line to insert through the plow. Using a minifig hand to connect to the hose, I also inserted a 3mm (Inside Diameter) flexible tube on the hand to simulate the end of the brake hose. The brake line insert that I've included has 8 parts in the .STL file because they are quite small and could break when being installed.

I've included two versions of the plow in this post - one with the brake line and one without.

UPDATE There are now three versions of the plow in this post - the newest one now has the ditch light tabs on the plow (see new pictures). I got tired of the ditch lights falling off when mounted on the porch of the loco. Everything else is still the same.

No commercial use of this model may be done without permission - in case anyone cares.

Upside-down Ikea letter tray mount

For mounting a Ikea DOKUMENT letter tray underneath a table. Please visit the github page for details, the sources and newest releases.

How to build one

Steps

How to customize

The only thing worth customizing might be the screw holes. The part is made with OpenSCAD, so you will need:

Dependencies

title: Martian II Receiver Antennas Mount V3

description.text:
This is a mount I did to adapt my X4R-SB receiver to a Martian II frame.

I designed this with printing in flexible filament in mind and even though I advice using such type of filament for the protection purposes it's meant I don't see why you couldn't use any other materials if you'd like to.
If you're printing with flexible filament do increase the scale in your slicer (around 5-10% depending on your filament's stretch properties) because it will shrink. 100% Scale is doable, it just makes it a bit more of a tight fit causing stress on the standoffs.

I redesigned this mount to be horizontal so it saves more space and is lightweight compared to my previous design.
Also the underbridge is to pass a zip tie between the mount and frame so it doesn't come out the frame to secure the Rx. This way it prevents of breaking the zip tie on a crash like it has happened to me.

This design does require support which is unadvised with flexible filaments but with the proper settings the supports do come out fairly easy.

Cheers.

title: Petsfang Duct for CR10 MicroSwiss/Stock/E3Dv6/Volcano/TevoTornado /Tarantula Hot End/E3Dv6 CNC Mount & 5015 fan or Stock fan&bed; leveling

description.text:
Petsfang Duct Cooling System

Currently supports the following printers:
Creality Cr10,S4,S5, Ender , TEVO Tornado and Tarantula

Hot Ends:
Micro Swiss Hot Ends
E3Dv6 and Volcano Hot Ends
Stock CR10 and TEVO Tornado Hot Ends
CNC Aluminum Mount for E3D Hot Ends

Fans:
Stock Radial Fan or 5015 Radial Fan Upgrade

Auto Bed Leveling Sensors:
TH3D EZABL and BL-Touch

All Tips are greatly appreciated.

PLEASE NOTE:
When I upgrade or re-design parts they will always be backward compatible. If I change anything on one part I will verify that it will fit on the prior parts. A base you downloaded 2 months ago will fit a duct I redesigned today.

For those of you asking for print orientation.......

3/8/2018
Modified modular wire strains for close tolerances to right and left rails and brought down 8mm to clear the wheel/bearings holding the back plate by 3mm.

3/2/2018
It was brought to my attention by member Silvio Garieri that the wire strain didn't allow for the full 400mm height to be used on his TEVO. I made a modular duct that can be used with our without the part. The wire strain with the wires attached will clear all aluminum guide rails. Of course if you didn't use the wire strain mod you had no issues with clearances anyway.

2/28/2018
Designed a cap for the E3Dv6 & Volcano mod to allow the use of the stock or upgraded 40mm fan to cool the hot end heat sink.

While I was at it I modified the interior of the duct to supports with some minimal fillets to allow it to print cleaner and easier, for those of you that had problem.

2/22/2018
Added E3D Volcano Duct.
Use the Bases with E3Dv6 & Volcano prefix.

2/21/2018
Member Joel Adams found his TEVO Tornado printed base fit tight on the base plate. I had Cappy De verify base plate thickness. It appears TEVO back plate is 3 tenths of a mm thicker than the CR10. I adjust TEVO files to reflect that thickness and make the base slide on easier.
Updated TEVO base files marked V2.21 are current.

2/18/2018
Added Youtube video showing duct printing orientation and supports
https://youtu.be/03R_0Qzzp4Q

7pm
Added TEVO Stockfan STL file
A couple of you said the Micro Swiss stock fan duct was a little tight to fit to the top of the TEVO Tornado base. I added 4mm for clearance and adjustment down to the nozzle in a seperate STL file.

2/17/2018
Independent testing from user Pemic showing airflow with water test. Pics.

2/16/2018
OK. This is going to be a lot of upgrade info……
Modifications to TEVO Parts
Worked with Thingiverse member Pemic on TEVO Tornado base mount.
Modifications to include.

  1. Large cutout in lower base to allow easier routing of hot end wires.
  2. Since this is a the Tornado is a CR10 clone it appears there is a little difference in the clearance to the X Gantry. Back clip for mounting adjusted .3mm to clear the gantry better.
  3. Because of the X gantry clearances I moved the EZABL and BL Touch to give better clearance and stay within back mounting base.

NEW
E3Dv6 Petsfan Duct mount for the popular CNC machined aluminum base.
Worked with Facebook member Cappy De to design a duct for the popular CNC mount for the E3Dv6 being sold on Ebay and other sites.
Cappy De was good enough to test print these mounts for me for fitment. They hold extremely firm to the CNC support and will be a good addition to that mount. You will notice that there are a lot of filets and weird angles to allow for a clean print with supports from build plate only. Don’t forget to set supports for these and check your slicer settings.

I want to thank you all for your support of this design and if you have a suggestion or questions please use MESSAGE on Thingiverse to contact me. I read every Message and don’t discount any suggestions. I’ll get back to you as soon as I can.

######## 2/13/2018 #########
A CR10s user had a problem with his stock hot end wires being able to be bent to the base side race relief. I put a small "back wall" extending from the race to keep your wires tidy and away from the X Carriage. I put a bigger lower relief at the heat block and widened the race. I did this to all MS-Stock and E3Dv6 bases. I test printed a base and it gives a lot more clearance for your hot end wires while maintaining the strength.
Also modified it to use a 20mm socket heat cap screw for the long thru screw in the front of the base. (It seems it's easier to get at a hardware store)

2/12/2018
6PM Central- Added wire race for hot end wires on the side of TEVO bases
4PM Central- TEVO base files uploaded.

Took the Tevo base files down temporarily. I forgot the fan holes. I am so sorry.

TEVO Tornado mounts are up. I have not seen a "Make" yet. Let me know how it fits.

E3Dv6 base with BL-Touch is uploaded.

2/10/2018
TEVO Tornado mount is done. Waiting on results from Beta testers before I post the STL files.

BL-Touch Base for Micro Swiss and Stock hot end uploaded.

This is an example of slicing and minimal supports in Cura for the bases. https://youtu.be/UtINRbHRHbE

2/8/2018
Fitting is done for E3Dv6. STL files are up. Will post the screws you'll need in notes. All are 3mm. Let me know how you like it.

I also renamed all the files with prefixes to show what fits with what.
MS-Stock prefix parts are for MicroSwiss or Stock Hotend.
E3Dv6 prefix parts are for E3dv6 Hotend.
Each similar prefix parts are interchangeable.

When mounting your E3Dv6 hot end make sure you mount the longer portion of the heat block forward. This keeps the heatsink cooling air from flowing over heat block and reducing the temp.

2/8/2018
Test printing of E3Dv6 base coming out better than expected. I purchased a V6 clone from TH3D and a CR10 metal base plate from Tiny Machines to use as my reference for installation tests. Some pics in upper pic area or in comments. Will release STL files when tests are done.
2/7/2018
Test printing the E3Dv6 Petsfang for fitment/ mounting and clearance. I'll keep you posted.

2/1/2018
I am working on base mounts for E3dv6 & Tevo Tornado. My main objective in my design besides the exceptional directional air flow, is to make everything very easy to print and mount (even for the novice). I design fillets, angles and radii to allow for printing with no or very minimal supports. Please bear with me on the E3dv6 and Tornado mounts as I have ordered the E3Dv6 and a CR10 X carriage replacement back to make sure my design works flawlessly with them.
Thanks, Dave

https://youtu.be/4Wmnu5MWhEY

1/29/2018 Update
Slaterbbx has installed this fan and is loving it. He made some great suggestions for changes which I incorporated in the new STL files with a prefix of 1-29. I have made no alterations that would affect the way these parts would fit with the original STL files. I have just given improved options. If you print any of these they will fit with the original files.
Here are some special settings that help print these with minimal supports as I originally designed. These settings are in CURA 3.1

Special for BASE printing

Support – EVERYWHERE
Support Overhang angle – 80%
Support Pattern – Zig Zag
Support Density – 20%

Special for DUCT Printing

1/26/2018
Added Petsfang Duct for stock radial fan. It will not be the velocity of the 5015 but will let you take advantage of the superior directional airflow this duct offers with the stock radial fan. I had someone ask for it, so here it is.

1/25/2018
Added base STL without the EZABL mount.

I have heard some of you don't like the 5015 because you can't control the fan speed. The windings in many of the 5015's don't like the PWM signal that is used to control the fan speed. PWM sends On and Off pulses to your fan. The length of these pulses cause the fan speed to change. To get around this you can wire in a 16v 220mf capacitor (I use these a lot of these in RC airplanes as voltage glitch busters and get them from Digikey) Solder the capacitor in parallel with the power. Capacitors have polarity so you will damage the cap and or your board if you wire it backwards. Caps have a polarity strip showing leg polarity on the side of the cap body. Wire negative to negative wire of your fan and positive to positive. I can get my cap to bleed down enough voltage that there is barely any air coming from my duct. It shows 1% on my CR10 display. Do not solder a cap in your system if you are not familiar with electronics. Be aware that caps have long legs and will have to be insulated clear up to the capacitor base to keep them from shorting out to the CR10 base or it's other leg. You do this at your own risk. It is 12v DC current.

1/22/2018
Did some bridging tests with this new duct. Test spanned 5mm x 200mm longest with no support on both X and Y axis. The duct cooled the filament allowing 200mm bridging with not one extrusion loss.
See test at:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2766559

1/20/2018
Installed my EZABL today with this duct. Took dimensions from my original Fusion design and used X-offset +48: Y-offset -2. It worked PERFECT! Love this duct blower and the EZABL.

1/16/2018
My last design worked well for what I was printing but an engineer friend saw it and gave me reasons to maximize the design. My buddy designs large commercial HVAC systems gave me a crash course on radial fans, static pressure, ductwork and outlets and why my original fang ducts weren’t utilizing the flow to cool the filament. Based on his info I created a design to maximize the airflow to the tip of the Micro Swiss hot end. Based on the 4.2 CFM of the 5015 fan I designed a large main duct for static pressure which reduces to 2 small rectangular outlets to convert the static pressure to directional velocity. There is a small baffle inside one duct to reduce the flow to that side which puts the turbulence just off the center of the nozzle tip. The duct can be adjusted up and down 1.5 mm to direct flow to the tip. It actually works incredibly well. The Youtube video is not real focused but you can see the airflow is right on the tip and drops off 2mm below and 2mm above the nozzle outlet. I’m going to try this with PETG to see if the bridging stays firm. I’m pretty happy with it. It should work with the stock hot end as well.
You can see in the video it pulls the paper just to the side of the tip and doesn't pick up the flow till 2mm from the tip.
https://youtu.be/p75VZrbXfDk

1/18/2018
Printed my first PETG ever.
Printed with this fang and layers and bridging worked great. Pic above in group. It is the white Hatchbox PETG.
245 degrees hot end and 70 bed temp.
Extended piece on the top of fang is for cable management.

Inthub,
I'm sorry.
I'm guessing you are in the UK?
In the US, SAE coarse screws have a # designation A #2 SAE screw is close to a 2mm. A #2 SAE or a 2mm metric will work for the side mounts on the duct. Since the back plate is a metric thread you should use a 3mm x 20mm standard pitch screw. The link for Home Depot should work just fine. Most hardware stores carry it in stock as well. When you Google the screws don't put in the spaces and you will get hundreds of pages for viewing. Google, 3mmx20mm screw.
In America #2 and #3 screws are common in woodworking and sheet metal.

comments.author: Omster

comments.text:
Omster,
With the holes in the center position you are 1.342mm above the nozzle tip. You want the outflow low enough to clear you heat block so it doesn't cool it down. You may have standard insulation or a silicone insulator heat sock on your machine. Make sure the air flow clears that. Simple answer. Keep it close to centered on the holes. 2mm clearance when the tip is flat on the bed is a good number. I run mine at 2.5mm from the bed.
Dave

comments.text: I like a couple of things on your design:
comments.author: PeteThings

comments.text:
PeteThings,
Let me address that based on current 3d printing information about glass transition temperatures and airflow directional velocity. All fangs (ducts) are hopefully designed to cool the extruding filament. As in the example of PLA filament the extruding temperature is 180-210 with a glass transition temperature of 60-65. Ideally you want to get your extruded filament to that temperature as quick as possible after this hot extruded filament has bonded to the underlying layer. All of the fang designs attempt to do that. Unfortunately most designs (not all) direct this airflow too far downward. This downward velocity causes the hot filament to be forced downward with that flow before it can reach the glass transition temperature. If you are printing one layer on top of another, this downward velocity would have little effect on the print. However, when printing any infill or large areas, that have significant bridging, this downward velocity warps the hot extruded filament causing poor bridging or a complete failure of the print. As you can see in my “Fan Challenge” testing the majority of directional velocity horizontal to the printing surface is limited to 1mm to .5mm below the nozzle with a very narrow flow directed on the nozzle. I think there is a misconception or maybe just a design issue, that air over the nozzle will affect the temperature or the ability to extrude. Since the heat block carries the majority of heat to transfer heat to the nozzle and melt the filament most of them are insulated. You are now seeing the advent of silicone sock insulators for this reason. In testing, the amount of air crossing my nozzle has never affected the outlet temperature for extruding purposes. Another part of the design I have to credit to my Engineering friend is the larger volume ducting chambers leading to the outlets. The larger volume ducts work as a flow regulator, it similar to a capacitor in electronics. It holds a volume of static pressure that will change in linear outflow rate with fan RPM increase. Once “pressurized” the ducts keep a steady volume of air flowing though the outlets. Most (not all) of the current fang designs have a “flow through” design with very little resistance down the duct. At 3 to 4 CFM of a standard 5015 Radial fan it equates to extreme amount of downward force against a very limp heated extruded filament that is trying to stay horizontal over bridging. In my tests I can get 200mm bridging with no problem. This is a result of the airflow passing horizontally over the limp filament not down into the print. I hope this information helps. Feel free to test it out. I am truly enjoying the results.
comments.author: PeteThings

comments.text:
Bossman74,
Not knowing the 5015 fan you have purchased I really can't give you an answer. I purchased a 5015 variable voltage (5-13.8 volts) and my 5015 fan comes down noticeably with the addition of the capacitor. Before I installed the cap my fan would not even start unless it was set to 100% due to it's inability to negotiate the PWM signal. Listen closely to your fan speed. It is probably turning at a slower RPM.

comments.text:
Bossman74,
It's not really the size of the cap it's the capacitance. I actually used a 2200uf for mine which is physically bigger but I just happen to keep them in stock. You may be able to find an physically smaller one but it needs to be the electrolytic type and 220uf at least 12 volt.

comments.text: The one with 28,000 members. But anyways man, just got this thing on my Cr-10 and HOLY CRAP it actually produces better results than stock that are visible. Honestly for normal things you don't need better than stock in my opinion but for bridging, oh yes. I have not hit it hard yet but the thing that blew my mind is that at .1 I could not see the layer beneath the top layer. I could only see the top layer lines. Looking at prints in comparison, I could always see my top 2 layers lines blended together, but with this thing cooling it the second it lays, the next layer beneath is completely invisible in my results. So that impressed me. Also With the way it is designed, it works great with the stock blower, honestly because you took into consideration how to actually control the airflow ( unlike normal fangs ) you can hear the sound of the airflow coming out of the duct tips even with the stock blower. Really impressive man, this thing is the first "Real deal" blower upgrade for the Cr-10, I especially like how it mounts, I can keep it in PLA when I start printing in other hotter plastics. I also really like the space it leaves behind the cold end, this allows for the proper intended cooling, most of the fangs bottleneck the airflow here. FANtastic work. lol, had to throw that in there.

description.text:
Inexpensive ball mill, about 4" / 100mm in diameter. I use a 5 volt 28BYJ-48 stepper motor and .5" glass marbles for the ball media. A PIC 12f675 / ULN2003 drives the cylinder at 45RPM. The powdered product tends to leak a bit. I place a dish under the mill to catch this.

I replaced the 5 volt stepper motor with its 12 volt counterpart. I've had less stalling issues with this setup.

Printing:
PLA
25 % infill on all parts except center.
Center setting: 0% infill. No top / no bottom.

Additional parts:
2 x 608ZZ bearings
6 x 4-40 x 2" stainless steel machine screws and nuts
1 x 28BYJ-48 stepper motor and driver
2 x #4 x .375" sheet metal screws
CA glue.

title: LEGO compatible print in place man

description.text:
As I looked at amazing printed in place things like LoboCNC's Iris Box (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1817180), Fidget spinner by muzz64 (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2237509), TikaDesign's Tika Alpaca (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2542369), I was wondering if I could be able to print something like this.

And here is printed in place LEGO compatible man! Sorry to say, that it is mostly a proof of concept, but still fully functional proof: he has movable legs, arms, hands, replaceable hat and swappable head. He can even seat and stand on the original and compatible surfaces and hold various items.

Spacing is large enough so that it is not exactly a stress test for your printer. Though you should level bed and make sure there is no such thing as elephant foot.

Man shoud easily (or relatively easily) move right after the print. But that depends on print settings and filament quality.

I used PLA for printing.

description.text: made as a mascot for my youtube channel, but i think he is a cool design to share anyway !

This is a redesign of the inner wheel to fit a LEGO Technic 43x22mm tyre. This model is designed to fit the motor inside the wheel instead of besides it, as shown in the photos (please excuse the shoddy soldering). The smaller footprint means the wheel is ideal for applications such as model RC cars or ant weight robots.

The wheel can hold a motor with a diameter of up to 24mm and a 2mm diameter shaft.

Print two for the front and one for the back.
The one for the back need to mount upwards and take care the endstop/case is not hit, even when you turn the knob. If you do not care, the printer can hit the knob when traveling to the home position and ruin your fine bed leveling adjustments. So take care nothing is hit the knob. If so, use a knife or sandpaper to remove sharp edges or other things who hit the case/endstop.

A chest from the Legend of Zelda games where the metal parts of the chest are 3d printed and the main body is made from popsicle sticks. I designed and built this for reddit secret santa 2017.

Video of how to build it:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=StWEeGEkwgs

The hinge mechanism uses some 1.75mm filament threaded through the printed parts.

The light and sound is provided by an Attiny85 (a really small arduino) and I used a old Nintendo DS Lite battery to power it (although any lithium-ion battery will work)
